  "text": "www.gsapubs.org | Volume 2 | Number 2 | LITHOSPHERE the existence or absence of a downwind plateau. The climate specifi c to each orogen displays an important latitudinal temperature gradient, and each longitudinally disposed terrane lies athwart the prevailing wind patterns. Mountain ranges are exceedingly complex, dynamic products of a broad range of processes not comprehensively treated here, but assuming the regional operation of isostasy, erosion due to rain and snowfall must be related somehow to the overall crustal thickness. However, as recently shown by [CITATION_1] , climate exerts a subsidiary role in controlling the elevation of the Andes.",
